<p><img align="left" width="100" src="/projects/RoverBluetooth/logo.png" style="position: relative; top: 8px; margin-bottom: 8px;" /> RoverBluetooth is the name I gave to the Arduino-based <strong>Bluetooth</strong> car I made for my school exam when I was only thirteen. I also showed it at <strong><a href="http://www.makerfairerome.eu/">Maker Faire Rome</a></strong> with a FabLab (and I was one of the youngest there)! It‚Äôs very easy to make (only a few low-cost electronic components and a Meccano pack) and to control, thanks to the <strong>Android</strong> app I programmed. It features full speed control, reverse gear, an ultrasonic sensor with parking sound and emergency brake, low-latency remote drive and a frontal light.</p>

<h3 id="the-app">The app</h3>

